i was further playing around with the following policy.json:
```
{
    "default": [
        {
            "type": "reject"
        }
    ],
    "transports": {
        "docker": {
            "cr.example.com/group1/subgroup1/repo1/debian": [
                {
                    "type": "sigstoreSigned",
                    "keyPath": "/etc/containers/signing-key.pem",
                    "signedIdentity": {
                        "type": "matchRepository"
                    }
                }
            ],
            " cr.example.com/group2/repo2": [
                {
                    "type": "sigstoreSigned",
                    "keyPath": "/etc/containers/signing-key.pem",
                    "signedIdentity": {
                        "type": "remapIdentity",
                        "prefix": " cr.example.com/group2/repo2/*",
                        "signedPrefix": "cr.example.com/group1/subgroup1/*"
                    }
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
```

It seems podman does not support wildcards. How can I tell podman to remap the identities for a mirror use case and only accept the signed images: 
eg
all images are build and signed in there respective repo 
- cr.example.com/group1/subgroup1/repo1/debian:latest
- cr.example.com/group1/subgroup1/repo1/debian:bookworm
- cr.example.com/group1/subgroup1/repo2/ubuntu:latest
- cr.example.com/group1/subgroup1/repo3/arch:latest

... and then mirrored including their signatures from the original build repo to a different release subgroup and repo: 
cr.example.com/group2/releases 

Thanks
